All you can eat sushi is always a gamble.  In this case, it worked out in our favor.  The food tasted good, and the all-you-can-eat deal included appetizers, drinks, maki rolls, sashimi, nigiri, and specialty rolls.  We ordered a pretty large initial batch, which they brought out in a paced fashion; as we finished a plate, they would swap it out for a new plate full of food.  Once we finished our initial batch, service got a bit slower, but we were able to get refills on our waters and soda before they announced "last call" before closing.  We ordered a second round of just nigiri at last call to cap off the evening, which worked out well to quench any remaining hunger.  With that said, you may ask why it was only given 4 stars.  I think it is very close to earning 5 stars, but there were a few things that I think need to be improved upon for a full 5 star rating.  First and foremost, better service.  Wait staff should be checking on you very shortly after you finish a plate to let you know that another is coming or to offer you the option to order more.  Secondly, it would be nice to see more options on their list of maki rolls.  There were no options for smoked salmon rolls despite offering smoked salmon as sashimi/nigiri, and most rolls had spicy mayo, which I dislike.  Also having more options with unagi would be appreciated as well.  So overall, a great experience, and we will come back, but I would love to see the above improvements next time we come in.

Food allergies beware!  I went to the Wasabi Cafe looking forward to a good meal, having seen online that they had good vegetarian options. Little did I know that I was about to have one of the most uncomfortable and insulting experiences of my life in a restaurant. I informed our waitress that I had an avocado allergy, and she told me to order the "all you can eat" sushi on a separate paper from the rest of the group (which seemed sensible to me). 10 minutes after ordering, a man (who I found out was the owner, Paul) came over and asked who had the allergy, and told me he couldn't guarantee that the cutting boards and knives they used were clean, so I should order from the "kitchen menu." I was incredibly uncomfortable about his inability to guarantee hygienic food preparation, but took the menu and ordered from it, assuming that he meant I needed to order from the normal menu. Another 10 minutes later he came over again, even more rudely chastised me for having ordered from the menu, saying I didn't order a "kitchen meal." I asked him several times what he wanted me to order, and told him I didn't understand what a “kitchen meal” was, and he proceeded to ignore my question and repeatedly tell me why he couldn't guarantee my food would be free of avocado and why people with my allergy couldn’t eat their food. He offered me free edamame, which I I refused since we already had 2 plates of edamame, and because edamame isn’t a meal. He kept harassing me even when I said it was fine and that I didn’t want to order anything else, and I clearly wanted to be left alone.  I eventually had to tell him that he was making me uncomfortable and that I simply wouldn't eat dinner, and he kept criticizing my ordering. I had to insist that he leave because at this point he was embarrassing me in front of my group and making me feel like my allergy was an insurmountable inconvenience, not something that restaurants have to deal with on a daily basis. Since I hadn't gotten any food of my own, I started noshing on the shared food we had ordered at the beginning of the meal when I had ordered the first time. Paul then came over in a huff and told me I couldn't eat the spring rolls or edamame we had because I wasn't paying for for the sushi menu (which I would have gladly paid for if they had let me order from it).  He essentially refused to serve me because of my allergy, and then told me I couldn’t eat food I had ordered as part of a group while planning to partake in the family style food. This restaurant is despicable. This was one of the worst and most uncomfortable experiences of my life. Nobody with allergies, food restrictions, or an expectation of basic respect should ever eat at this restaurant. Paul in particular should not be allowed to speak to customers, especially women, who he obviously doesn't respect. I have never been so appalled at service, or been made to feel so ashamed in a restaurant for having a food allergy.

My favorite sushi place in North Center. The ambiance is not as great as some other places, but the fish quality is very good. Great buffet-style Sushi restaurant. You pay per person, so make sure you bring an appetite. The pricing is fair, it is cheaper if you pay cash.  The way you order here was unique to me at first but it is a great system. The waiter/waitress will bring you a menu, you mark down how many sets of each item. After you are done, you press a button that calls over your server and they take the menu. After your food is done, they bring it out as many at a time as possible.  The food is delicious. I've haven't been to a Sushi restaurant where the fish is that fresh. They have a huge variety of items to pick, from the Avocado roll to the Dragon roll, from the Spicy Tuna to the Rainbow roll. They also have other items apart from rolls, such as crab ragoons.  Overall, really great experience with fresh Sushi. I would definitely come again.

Came and found (to my surprise) that there's an all you can eat option.  Like other sushi spots offering AYCE, there are some rules.  If you've never done all you can eat sushi here are some tips. - Do not go it alone.  You'll get more bang for your buck and variety if you have someone or someoneS (preferably with big stomachs) to share the experience with. - You have to eat everything you order. Some exceptions do apply but waste is not an option.  Order wisely and get group buy-in before committing to an entire maki. - Don't bother filling up on non-sushi items.  You've gotta put your game face on and be ready to eat your dollars worth in rolls.  Find a balance between liquid and solid. - Most importantly: Know thyself.  You're in it to win it but there's no reason to hurt yourself.  Eat within your limits. Bonus tip: It's probably wisest not to take a date on an all you can eat excursion.  You will look like a fat pig and that's just not sexy.  My experience here is as it has been at other AYCE places.  It's hard to find fault in an all you can eat joint that is clean, friendly, and responsive.  Wasabi Cafe hits all of these.  Admittedly I am a sushi snob.  I've come to grips that I'm not going to have my freshness or variety needs satisfied here in the midwest.  If I'm craving and in starved like a crazed animal mode, I'll definitely head on over to Wasabi Cafe and have a good time.  Price is about what you'd expect and I found everything more than palatable.  Come.  Bring your friends.  Do it up big time.
